[1]
Date: 22 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New York Times [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/22/international/middleeast/22polio.html>

Polio back in Yemen after 6 year absence
----------------------------------------
Polio has broken out in Yemen and may have been imported by pilgrims
returning from Mecca, international health officials said yesterday. The
disease appeared to have been on the verge of eradication in early 2004,
but has since spread to several countries across Africa and Saudi Arabia.
4 children paralyzed by polio have been found in Yemen, which is tucked
into a corner of the Arabian peninsula, and shares a long, porous border
with Saudi Arabia.
In response, the Yemeni government and the World Health Organization are
planning immunization drives for May and July 2005 in an effort to get
drops of oral polio vaccine into the mouths of all 5 million Yemeni children.
Last week, Yemen held its first such drive since 2001. The health minister,
Dr Yehya Mohammed al-Noami, said then that polio had not been seen in Yemen
since 1999 but that a surge of new cases in Saudi Arabia, Sudan, and
Ethiopia made precautions necessary.
Yesterday, a spokesman for the Yemeni Embassy in Washington said he knew
nothing about the new cases and referred a reporter to the government news
service Web site, which had no information about it posted.
WHO is struggling to find money to contain resurgent polio. 2 extra drives
in Yemen will cost over USD 2 million; at the same time, the agency's USD
25 million polio emergency fund has been depleted of all but USD 500 000
because of efforts in Sudan and Ethiopia, said Dr Bruce Aylward, the
agency's global polio eradication coordinator.
The Yemeni children found to have polio, aged 18 months to 7 years, are all
in the Red Sea port of Al Hudaida and first showed signs of paralysis in
February or early March [2005], said Dr Mohamed H Wahdan, WHO's Eastern
Mediterranean polio coordinator. In poor countries, it can take weeks to
confirm a polio case, because stool samples must be sent to distant
laboratories.
All of the children had been vaccinated, Dr Wahdan said, but apparently not
enough times. In countries with hot weather, open sewers and many other
intestinal viruses, it can take 6 to 8 doses of vaccine to produce the same
immunity that 3 or 4 do in cooler, cleaner countries.
Only about one case in 200 leads to paralysis, so there could be at least
800 more carriers in Yemen, and Dr Wahdan said he expected to find more
cases. [The ratio of paralytic cases to infected individuals ranges from a
high of 1 in 50 to a low of 1 in 1000 - Mod.MPP] He said virus samples had
been sent to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta for
genotyping, which should reveal their origins.
In early February [2005], after 2 cases were found near Mecca, Dr Aylward
said he feared that some of the 2 million returning pilgrims could spread
the disease. "If I had to make a bet about where it would strike first,
Yemen would be it," he said yesterday. "But there's as much traffic into
Yemen from Sudan as there is from Saudi Arabia, so it's just as likely it
came from there."
Despite the small population and poverty of Yemen, Dr Wahdan said Yemen has
"lots of traffic." Many citizens work in wealthy Persian Gulf states, many
Sudanese teach in Yemeni schools, and African traders move through on their
way to the gulf.
A Saudi official said earlier this year that tens of thousands of people
enter his country illegally each month through Yemen. The bleak desert they
share is named the Empty Quarter and the border is officially undefined.
Sudan is having a major polio outbreak, particularly in Port Sudan, a Red
Sea ferry port.
All the migrating strains originated in Nigeria. 3 largely Muslim states in
northern Nigeria stopped vaccinating in 2003 after rumors spread that the
vaccine was a Western plot to sterilize Muslim women, that it transmitted
AIDS, and that it contained pork products.
They resumed vaccinations in mid-2004 after entreaties from top Muslim
clerics and after state officials visited foreign vaccine factories. But by
then new cases were turning up from the Atlantic to the Red Sea and as far
south as Botswana. "This is the low season for polio," Dr Aylward said, "so
we look for importation cases. These things come across borders like sparks
from a forest fire falling on dry tinder. Usually we're able to knock it
out quickly, like we did in Botswana last year, or in 2003 when we had an
import from India into Lebanon, or in 2001 when we had cases in Georgia and
Bulgaria. "But we've exhausted our emergency reserve. So the great news is
that cases are plummeting in Nigeria and Niger and India and Pakistan. But
our ability to respond to these sparks in dry tinder is way, way down.
We're really scrambling."
[byline: Donald G McNeil Jr]
