Date: 22 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Polio Eradication Website / WHO position statement 22 Apr 2005
[edited]
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/YemenFinalPositionStatement22April2005.pdf
>

WHO position statement on 4 polio cases reported from Yemen
-----------------------------------------------------------
On 20 Apr [2005], 4 polio cases due to wild poliovirus type 1 were
confirmed in Yemen. The cases were reported from Hudeida governorate in
southwest Yemen, on the Red Sea coast. Prior to these cases, wild
poliovirus has not been found in Yemen since AFP surveillance began in 1996.
Situation
---------
On 4 April WHO Yemen was informed by Hudeida governorate health authorities
of a cluster of acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) cases in children, the 1st
cases of which had occurred in February 2005. The cases had been detected
through AFP surveillance activities and investigated, including collection
of stool specimens for laboratory investigation.
On 18 Apr [2005], in close coordination with local health authorities, 2
teams of WHO and Ministry of Health experts, including epidemiologists and
paediatricians, were dispatched to Hudeida governorate to further
investigate the cluster of AFP cases.
On 20 Apr [2005], results of testing of stool specimens of 4 of the cases
by the polio network laboratory in Oman revealed wild poliovirus type 1.
The laboratory and field investigation of other AFP cases is ongoing, and
additional information will be made public as soon as it is available,
including genetic information which will help identify the origin of the
wild poliovirus responsible for the cases.
WHO response
------------
Yemen has already conducted a nationwide immunization campaign on 13-15 Apr
[2005], to immunize all of the country's 4.5 million children under the age
of 5 years. WHO is working with the Ministry of Health in Yemen to plan for
further intensive house-to-house immunization activities in the immediate
geographic vicinity of the cases. Planning for the next nationwide
immunization campaign to be conducted in the 2nd half of May [2005] is
being intensified. Contingency plans for a potential 3rd campaign in June
[2005] are being discussed. Additional technical support is being provided
for the continuing investigation and for planning for immunization rounds.
WHO is working with the Ministry of Health in Yemen to ensure that AFP
surveillance throughout the country is sensitized so that no transmission
of wild poliovirus is missed. Additionally, Ministries of Health of
neighbouring countries have been informed.
Important note
--------------
The risk of importations into polio-free areas remains as long as polio
exists anywhere in the world. WHO urges all countries to maintain and
strengthen AFP surveillance and high population immunity.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The occurrence of cases in Yemen is yet another setback in the global
effort to eradicate polio. Information on the most recent case counts
worldwide as of 19 Apr 2005 can be found at the polio eradication website
<http://www.polioeradication.org>. The cases in Yemen are not on the most
current table, as they were officially reported on 20 Apr 2005, the day
after the most recent update. It will be interesting to see the genetic
profile of the poliovirus involved to determine the origin of the virus,
although the likelihood of it being related to the ongoing outbreak in the
Sudan (which in turn was related to the ongoing outbreak in Nigeria) is
high. Whether these cases were related to travel through Mecca also awaits
to be seen. However, the identification of 4 cases strongly suggests that
whatever the original source of the virus, there is/was current ongoing
transmission in the involved area in Yemen. Credit goes to the Yemeni
Ministry of Health for conducting a national vaccination campaign while
results of the laboratory testing of the AFP cases were still pending. -
Mod.MPP]
